Car Insurance Premium by state¶

In [3]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

sns.set(style="whitegrid")

# Sort states by Car Insurance Premiums for better visualization
df_sorted = df.sort_values(by='Car Insurance Premiums ($)', ascending=False)

# Create the bar chart
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))
sns.barplot(x='Car Insurance Premiums ($)', y='State', data=df_sorted, palette='viridis')

# Set title and labels
plt.title('Car Insurance Premiums by State', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Car Insurance Premiums ($)', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('State', fontsize=10)

# Show the plot
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Top 10 states¶

In [5]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Function to plot top 10 states for each numeric column
def plot_top_10(df, column, title):
    top_10 = df[['State', column]].sort_values(by=column, ascending=False).head(10)
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.barh(top_10['State'], top_10[column], color='skyblue')
    plt.xlabel(column)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.gca().invert_yaxis()  # Invert y-axis to have the highest value at the top
    plt.show()

# List of numeric columns to plot
columns_to_plot = [
    'Number of drivers involved in fatal collisions per billion miles',
    'Percentage Of Drivers Involved In Fatal Collisions Who Were Speeding',
    'Percentage Of Drivers Involved In Fatal Collisions Who Were Alcohol-Impaired',
    'Percentage Of Drivers Involved In Fatal Collisions Who Were Not Distracted',
    'Percentage Of Drivers Involved In Fatal Collisions Who Had Not Been Involved In Any Previous Accidents',
    'Car Insurance Premiums ($)',
    'Losses incurred by insurance companies for collisions per insured driver ($)'
]

# Plot each column with the top 10 states
for column in columns_to_plot:
    plot_top_10(df, column, f"Top 10 States by {column}")

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Function to plot least 10 states for each numeric column
def plot_least_10(df, column, title):
    least_10 = df[['State', column]].sort_values(by=column, ascending=True).head(10)
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.barh(least_10['State'], least_10[column], color='skyblue')
    plt.xlabel(column)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.show()

# List of numeric columns to plot
columns_to_plot = [
    'Number of drivers involved in fatal collisions per billion miles',
    'Percentage Of Drivers Involved In Fatal Collisions Who Were Speeding',
    'Percentage Of Drivers Involved In Fatal Collisions Who Were Alcohol-Impaired',
    'Percentage Of Drivers Involved In Fatal Collisions Who Were Not Distracted',
    'Percentage Of Drivers Involved In Fatal Collisions Who Had Not Been Involved In Any Previous Accidents',
    'Car Insurance Premiums ($)',
    'Losses incurred by insurance companies for collisions per insured driver ($)'
]

# Plot each column with the least 10 states
for column in columns_to_plot:
    plot_least_10(df, column, f"Least 10 States by {column}")

Correlation with Car Insurance Premium and Losses Incurred by Insurance Companies¶

In [7]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Correlation data for Car Insurance Premiums ($)
premiums_correlation = {
    'Number of drivers in fatal collisions': -0.20,
    'Percentage speeding': 0.04,
    'Percentage alcohol-impaired': -0.02,
    'Percentage not distracted': 0.02,
    'Percentage no previous accidents': 0.08,
    'Losses incurred by insurance': 0.62
}

# Correlation data for Losses Incurred by Insurance Companies ($)
losses_correlation = {
    'Number of drivers in fatal collisions': -0.04,
    'Percentage speeding': -0.06,
    'Percentage alcohol-impaired': -0.08,
    'Percentage not distracted': -0.06,
    'Percentage no previous accidents': 0.04
}

# Function to plot correlation bar chart
def plot_correlation(correlation_dict, title):
    categories = list(correlation_dict.keys())
    values = list(correlation_dict.values())

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    bars = plt.barh(categories, values, color='lightcoral')
    plt.xlabel('Correlation')
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlim(-1, 1)
    
    # Add the correlation values to the bars
    for bar in bars:
        width = bar.get_width()
        plt.text(width, bar.get_y() + bar.get_height() / 2,
                 f'{width:.2f}', va='center', ha='left' if width > 0 else 'right')

    plt.gca().invert_yaxis()  # Invert y-axis for readability
    plt.show()

# Plot the correlations for both variables
plot_correlation(premiums_correlation, 'Correlation with Car Insurance Premiums ($)')
plot_correlation(losses_correlation, 'Correlation with Losses Incurred by Insurance Companies ($)')

Analysis of Traffic Accidents in Connecticut¶

In [19]:
import pandas as pd

# Defining the columns of interest
numeric_columns = [
    'Number of drivers involved in fatal collisions per billion miles',
    'Percentage Of Drivers Involved In Fatal Collisions Who Were Speeding',
    'Percentage Of Drivers Involved In Fatal Collisions Who Were Alcohol-Impaired',
    'Percentage Of Drivers Involved In Fatal Collisions Who Were Not Distracted',
    'Percentage Of Drivers Involved In Fatal Collisions Who Had Not Been Involved In Any Previous Accidents',
    'Car Insurance Premiums ($)',
    'Losses incurred by insurance companies for collisions per insured driver ($)'
]

# Calculating metrics for comparison
analysis_data = {'Column': [], 'Connecticut Value': [], 'Average Value': [], 'Max Value': [], 'Min Value': [], 'Connecticut Rank': [], 'Position': []}

# Loop through each column and calculate the necessary metrics
for col in numeric_columns:
    # Get Connecticut's value
    connecticut_value = data.loc[data['State'] == 'Connecticut', col].values[0]

    # Calculate average, max, and min values for the column
    avg_value = data[col].mean()
    max_value = data[col].max()
    min_value = data[col].min()

    # Rank of Connecticut for the column
    rank = data[col].rank(ascending=False)[data['State'] == 'Connecticut'].values[0]

    # Determine Connecticut's position relative to the average
    position = 'Above Average' if connecticut_value > avg_value else 'Below Average'

    # Add data to the summary
    analysis_data['Column'].append(col)
    analysis_data['Connecticut Value'].append(connecticut_value)
    analysis_data['Average Value'].append(avg_value)
    analysis_data['Max Value'].append(max_value)
    analysis_data['Min Value'].append(min_value)
    analysis_data['Connecticut Rank'].append(int(rank))
    analysis_data['Position'].append(position)

# Convert to a DataFrame for analysis
analysis_df = pd.DataFrame(analysis_data)

# Display the analysis table
print(analysis_df)

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Filter data for the selected states
states_to_compare = ["Connecticut", "New York", "New Jersey", "Massachusetts", "New Hampshire"]
filtered_data = data[data['State'].str.strip().isin(states_to_compare)]

# List of insurance-related metrics with descriptive titles
insurance_metrics = [
    ("Car Insurance Premiums ($)", "Average Car Insurance Premiums ($)"),
    ("Losses incurred by insurance companies for collisions per insured driver ($)", "Insurance Losses per Insured Driver ($)")
]

# Set the DPI for high-quality output
dpi = 300

# Generate a high-quality bar chart for each insurance metric
for metric, title in insurance_metrics:
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4), dpi=dpi)  # Larger size and higher DPI for quality
    plt.bar(filtered_data['State'].str.strip(), filtered_data[metric], color='mediumseagreen')
    
    # Titles and labels
    plt.title(title, fontsize=14, weight='bold')
    plt.xlabel("State", fontsize=10)
    plt.ylabel(metric, fontsize=8)
    
    # Improve layout and readability
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, fontsize=10)
    plt.yticks(fontsize=10)
    plt.tight_layout()
    
    # Save the image with high quality
    plt.savefig(f"{title}.png", format='png', dpi=dpi)  # Save as PNG with high DPI
    plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# List of only percentage-based metrics and their titles for individual plotting
percentage_metrics = [
    ("Percentage Of Drivers Involved In Fatal Collisions Who Were Speeding", "% Fatal Collisions Who Were Speeding"),
    ("Percentage Of Drivers Involved In Fatal Collisions Who Were Alcohol-Impaired", "% Fatal Collisions Who Were Alcohol-Impaired"),
    ("Percentage Of Drivers Involved In Fatal Collisions Who Were Not Distracted", "% Fatal Collisions Who Were Not Distracted"),
    ("Percentage Of Drivers Involved In Fatal Collisions Who Had Not Been Involved In Any Previous Accidents", "% Fatal Collisions with No Prior Accidents")
]

# Set the DPI for high-quality output
dpi = 300

# Generate a high-quality bar chart for each percentage-based metric
for metric, title in percentage_metrics:
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5), dpi=dpi)  # Larger size and higher DPI for quality
    plt.bar(filtered_data['State'].str.strip(), filtered_data[metric], color='cornflowerblue')
    
    # Titles and labels with larger fonts
    plt.title(title, fontsize=12, weight='bold')
    plt.xlabel("State", fontsize=10)
    plt.ylabel(metric, fontsize=8)
    
    # Improve layout and readability
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, fontsize=10)
    plt.yticks(fontsize=10)
    plt.tight_layout()
    
    # Save each chart as a high-quality PNG image
    plt.savefig(f"{title}.png", format='png', dpi=dpi)  # Save as PNG with high DPI
    plt.show()
